SIMPLE: unction
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Unction
<hw>Unc"tion</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>unccioun</ets>, <ets>uncioun</ets>, OF. <ets>oncion</ets>,
<ets>onction</ets>, F. <ets>onction</ets>, fr. L. <ets>unctio</ets>, fr.
<ets>ungere</ets>, <ets>unctum</ets>, to anoint. See
<er>Unguent</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of anointing,
smearing, or rubbing with an unguent, oil, or ointment, especially for
medical purposes, or as a symbol of consecration; <as>as, mercurial
<ex>unction</ex></as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To be heir, and to be king⟦br⟧
By sacred <qex>unction</qex>, thy deserved right.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>That which is used for anointing; an unguent; an
ointment; hence, anything soothing or lenitive.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The king himself the sacred <qex>unction</qex> made.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Lay not that flattering <qex>unction</qex> to your soul.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Divine or sanctifying grace.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>That quality in language, address, or the like,
which excites emotion; especially, strong devotion; religious fervor and
tenderness; sometimes, a simulated, factitious, or unnatural
fervor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The delightful equivoque and <qex>unction</qex> of the passage in
Farquhar.</q> <rj><qau>Hazlitt.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The mention of thy glory⟦br⟧
Is <qex>unction</qex> to the breast.</q> <rj><qau>Neale (Rhythm of St.
Bernard).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Extreme unction</b></col> <fld>(R. C. Ch. & Gr.
Ch.)</fld>, <cd>the sacrament of anointing in the last hours; the
application of consecrated oil by a priest to all the senses, that is,
to eyes, ears, nostrils, etc., of a person when in danger of death from
illness, -- done for remission of sins.</cd> <mark>[James v. 14,
15.]</mark></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Unctious</ent>⟦br⟧
